On April 30, 2010, all of the outstanding common stock of 1st Financial Bank wa acquired by Aslin Group, Inc. in exchange for a cash payment of $1. Concurrent with the acquisition, 1st Financial Bank was renamed Alterra Bank (the Bank). At that date, the Bank's liabilities exceeded its assets by $3,012,267. The acquisition was accounted for under the provisions of FASB ASC 805 (SFAS 141R. Business Combinations). Accordingly, the Bank adjusted the carrying values of the acquired tabgible and identifiable intangible assets and the assumed liabilities to their estimated fair values. 2. In addition, the Bank recorded goodwill of $2,631,117. FASB ASC 805 allows a measurement period of up to one year to adjust initial fair value estimates as an additional information regarding such fair values as of the acquisition date becomes available. 3. Concurrent with the acquisition of the Bank, Aslin Group, Inc. contributed additional cash capital of $12,500,000 to the Bank, which represents the opening shareholders equity balance as of April 30, 2010. 4. As a result of the application of FASB ASC 805 and ASC 310-30, the April 30, 2010 balance sheet for Alterra Bank did not include an allowance for loan losses. The current provision and allowance for loan losses reflected as of June 30 is related to the growth in the loan portfolio since the acquisition.??5. Income reported in Schedules RI represents income since the acquisition date. 6. Quarterly Averages reported on Schedule RC-K represent average balances from April 30, 2010 through June 30, 2010.

Prior to FASB 166, this income would have been recorded as earnings, and net earnings as of June 30, 2010 would have been $1,123,000. FASB 166 also results in sold loans being recorded as "loans" and "secured borrowings" for a period of 90 days. As a result, the Bank's loans held for sale and borrowings are ovestated by $28.4million and $31.4 million, respectively, as of June 30, 2010. Leverage, Tier 1 and Total Risk ratios would have been 9.95%, 13.16%, 14.52%, as of June 30, 2010 had FAS 166 not been implemented.

In March 2007, the Bank received a one time allocation of $8.6 million in overhead. Effective 4/1/07, the Bank has entered into an agreement with its parent which states that the parent agrees not to allocate any overhead to the Bank until its net income, after allocation exceeds $2 million for a period of three years. Legg Mason Investment Council and Trust Company , NA ("Bank") now assesses and monitors its capital, capital needs and liquidity on a quarterly basis throug  its Investment Policy Committee.
